1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,200
 Amen, amen, amen.

2
00:00:03,200 --> 00:00:06,680
 Well, I'm really excited that this afternoon

3
00:00:06,680 --> 00:00:09,200
 we get to host one of our speakers

4
00:00:09,200 --> 00:00:11,640
 that's been with us this whole weekend.

5
00:00:11,640 --> 00:00:15,200
 And as I said earlier, we've had about 35 different speakers

6
00:00:15,200 --> 00:00:19,880
 throughout the course of this time during the conference.

7
00:00:19,880 --> 00:00:23,000
 And it's been such a joy to hear from different perspectives

8
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:25,840
 and just different people and different backgrounds.

9
00:00:25,840 --> 00:00:28,480
 But each person brought their own story.

10
00:00:28,480 --> 00:00:30,840
 Each person brought their own context.

11
00:00:30,840 --> 00:00:33,480
 And one of the people that when we were thinking

12
00:00:33,480 --> 00:00:35,040
 about curating this conference

13
00:00:35,040 --> 00:00:37,480
 and wanting to make sure that we were hearing

14
00:00:37,480 --> 00:00:39,440
 from the right voices,

15
00:00:39,440 --> 00:00:40,960
 you can understand that there's so much

16
00:00:40,960 --> 00:00:42,120
 that's happening around the world,

17
00:00:42,120 --> 00:00:46,280
 but there's voices that we need to hear from

18
00:00:46,280 --> 00:00:47,720
 at times like this.

19
00:00:47,720 --> 00:00:52,720
 And Dr. Lamaman Soor was a person that we were led to.

20
00:00:52,720 --> 00:00:55,400
 I actually, she was recommended to us

21
00:00:55,400 --> 00:00:59,720
 by a good friend of ours who does work in the Middle East,

22
00:00:59,720 --> 00:01:02,600
 a work of peace and reconciliation in the land there.

23
00:01:02,600 --> 00:01:04,480
 And they said, look, you have to get this lady,

24
00:01:04,480 --> 00:01:07,120
 you have to get her voice into the conference.

25
00:01:07,120 --> 00:01:10,000
 And so I did the right thing and Googled,

26
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:11,960
 that's what you do these days.

27
00:01:11,960 --> 00:01:15,760
 And sat and watched a talk that she gave on lament

28
00:01:15,760 --> 00:01:17,480
 at a conference in the Middle East.

29
00:01:17,480 --> 00:01:19,200
 And it just blew me away.

30
00:01:19,200 --> 00:01:24,200
 And she's a Palestinian Christian based in Nazareth.

31
00:01:25,200 --> 00:01:27,360
 She is a social scientist by background,

32
00:01:27,360 --> 00:01:29,200
 has a doctorate and master's from Oxford,

33
00:01:29,200 --> 00:01:31,600
 as well as a bachelor's degree in psychology

34
00:01:31,600 --> 00:01:33,840
 from the University of Haifa.

35
00:01:33,840 --> 00:01:36,640
 But I think more than any of that,

36
00:01:36,640 --> 00:01:40,080
 she is a pastoral prophetic voice in a time

37
00:01:40,080 --> 00:01:42,840
 on behalf of her own people,

38
00:01:42,840 --> 00:01:45,280
 in a time where her people are facing

39
00:01:45,280 --> 00:01:49,960
 such horrendous oppression.

40
00:01:49,960 --> 00:01:52,880
 And for her to take some time to come out of that

41
00:01:52,880 --> 00:01:55,360
 and come here and just be present with us

42
00:01:55,360 --> 00:01:59,240
 over this weekend is a profound gift for us.

43
00:01:59,240 --> 00:02:01,160
 And it's important that we open our hearts

44
00:02:01,160 --> 00:02:03,960
 to what is happening around the world.

45
00:02:03,960 --> 00:02:05,560
 But the thing that's so beautiful about Lama,

46
00:02:05,560 --> 00:02:10,560
 despite just what her people are facing at this time,

47
00:02:10,560 --> 00:02:14,600
 the gift of hope that sits within her is truly profound.

48
00:02:14,600 --> 00:02:16,920
 And so I'm gonna shut up

49
00:02:16,920 --> 00:02:20,000
 because I'm just so excited that we can welcome her.

50
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:22,400
 So can we put our hands together as Lama comes?

51
00:02:22,920 --> 00:02:25,680
 (congregation applauding)

52
00:02:25,680 --> 00:02:28,520
 And we're gonna pray for you.

53
00:02:28,520 --> 00:02:31,840
 Let's stretch out our hands.

54
00:02:31,840 --> 00:02:32,920
 Actually, why don't we stand?

55
00:02:32,920 --> 00:02:34,880
 I think that would be the honorable thing to do.

56
00:02:34,880 --> 00:02:38,320
 Why don't we stretch out our hands and pray for Lama?

57
00:02:38,320 --> 00:02:41,720
 Her name is spelt like the island Lama,

58
00:02:41,720 --> 00:02:42,880
 just want you to know.

59
00:02:42,880 --> 00:02:46,000
 She was very excited when she discovered that, weren't you?

60
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:47,800
 You were very excited about that, okay.

61
00:02:47,800 --> 00:02:49,800
 Father, just thank you so much for Lama

62
00:02:49,800 --> 00:02:54,800
 and for just what she represents, Lord.

63
00:02:54,800 --> 00:02:58,000
 We thank you for her people.

64
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:02,320
 And we know that they're going through a horrendous time.

65
00:03:02,320 --> 00:03:06,680
 Lord, we lift them before you now.

66
00:03:06,680 --> 00:03:10,080
 Father, we stand in solidarity.

67
00:03:10,080 --> 00:03:14,560
 We pray that you would move our hearts and our lips.

68
00:03:16,440 --> 00:03:20,320
 And Father, as we sit under this teaching this afternoon,

69
00:03:20,320 --> 00:03:23,760
 we pray that you would speak to us personally.

70
00:03:23,760 --> 00:03:27,400
 Lord, each one of us has a journey and a story.

71
00:03:27,400 --> 00:03:31,360
 And so as Lama shares from hers and from her people,

72
00:03:31,360 --> 00:03:34,120
 Lord, would we connect ours to it

73
00:03:34,120 --> 00:03:37,080
 and feel that incredibly profound thing that happens

74
00:03:37,080 --> 00:03:39,240
 in the body of Christ around the world,

75
00:03:39,240 --> 00:03:42,520
 unity and solidarity together as we hear from you.

76
00:03:42,520 --> 00:03:44,320
 We thank you for this in Jesus' name.

77
00:03:44,320 --> 00:03:46,560
 Everyone says, amen, amen.

78
00:03:46,560 --> 00:03:51,560
 - Good afternoon.

79
00:03:51,560 --> 00:03:58,960
 I'm just so grateful this afternoon for the Vine,

80
00:03:58,960 --> 00:04:01,480
 for everyone here, for this weekend,

81
00:04:01,480 --> 00:04:04,560
 for Pastor Andrew and all of the team at the Vine.

82
00:04:04,560 --> 00:04:06,800
 I've been, I was just sharing with the team

83
00:04:06,800 --> 00:04:08,600
 that I've never been prayed for

84
00:04:08,600 --> 00:04:11,440
 as much as I have been in this weekend.

85
00:04:11,440 --> 00:04:14,160
 And I just feel covered by the Holy Spirit

86
00:04:14,160 --> 00:04:16,040
 and I know that there's a lot of work

87
00:04:16,040 --> 00:04:17,920
 that has been done in that.

88
00:04:17,920 --> 00:04:20,160
 I've just, yeah, just your hospitality,

89
00:04:20,160 --> 00:04:23,520
 your warmth has touched me very, very much.

90
00:04:23,520 --> 00:04:25,520
 So thank you, thank you for your heart.

91
00:04:25,520 --> 00:04:32,480
 I don't know if you know, but today, the 21st of September,

92
00:04:32,480 --> 00:04:36,400
 is the United Nations International Day of Peace.

93
00:04:36,400 --> 00:04:39,040
 So it's a day that the global organizations

94
00:04:39,040 --> 00:04:42,280
 have set aside for the pursuit of peace.

95
00:04:42,320 --> 00:04:47,320
 And for us as Palestinians, especially at a time like this,

96
00:04:47,320 --> 00:04:50,520
 it's difficult to talk and think about peace.

97
00:04:50,520 --> 00:04:54,080
 For us in the land, peace and justice

98
00:04:54,080 --> 00:04:56,080
 feel like a distant dream,

99
00:04:56,080 --> 00:05:01,680
 not realistic goals that can be achieved anytime soon.

100
00:05:01,680 --> 00:05:06,320
 The famous Palestinian poet, Mahmoud Darwish,

101
00:05:06,320 --> 00:05:09,160
 talks about, he has a saying.

102
00:05:09,160 --> 00:05:14,160
 In Arabic, he says, (speaking in foreign language)

103
00:05:14,160 --> 00:05:20,000
 Meaning, peace for a land that has been made for peace,

104
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:22,440
 but has never seen peace.

105
00:05:22,440 --> 00:05:23,560
 This is our heart.

106
00:05:23,560 --> 00:05:27,680
 For almost two years, our region has been embroiled

107
00:05:27,680 --> 00:05:29,680
 in violence we couldn't have imagined.

108
00:05:29,680 --> 00:05:32,840
 I'm sure you've followed the news.

109
00:05:32,840 --> 00:05:37,440
 1,200 Israelis killed on October 7th, 2023,

110
00:05:37,440 --> 00:05:41,240
 around 600 of which were civilians, non-combatants.

111
00:05:41,240 --> 00:05:45,320
 Hundreds wounded and taken hostage into Gaza,

112
00:05:45,320 --> 00:05:47,640
 many of whom are still waiting to be released.

113
00:05:47,640 --> 00:05:51,040
 Their families have such deep pain

114
00:05:51,040 --> 00:05:53,080
 waiting for them to return.

115
00:05:53,080 --> 00:05:54,840
 Many communities have been torn apart

116
00:05:54,840 --> 00:05:56,720
 by the violence that day.

117
00:05:56,720 --> 00:06:01,520
 In the Gaza Strip, the destruction is unbelievable.

118
00:06:01,520 --> 00:06:05,000
 Since that day, over 60,000 Palestinians

119
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:08,080
 in the Gaza Strip have been killed by Israel.

120
00:06:08,080 --> 00:06:12,280
 Tens of thousands wounded, hundreds arrested

121
00:06:12,280 --> 00:06:16,560
 and tortured in detention centers.

122
00:06:16,560 --> 00:06:19,320
 Entire families were wiped out from the civil registry.

123
00:06:19,320 --> 00:06:23,520
 Homes and schools and hospitals and universities

124
00:06:23,520 --> 00:06:26,360
 and churches and mosques have been bombed.

125
00:06:26,360 --> 00:06:29,200
 By one estimate, Israel has dropped

126
00:06:29,200 --> 00:06:33,320
 over 70,000 tons of munitions on Gaza.

127
00:06:33,320 --> 00:06:35,840
 Keep in mind that the Gaza Strip is tiny

128
00:06:35,840 --> 00:06:37,280
 and it's very, very dense.

129
00:06:37,280 --> 00:06:39,680
 It's almost as dense as Hong Kong.

130
00:06:39,680 --> 00:06:43,480
 People's entire lives have been turned upside down.

131
00:06:43,480 --> 00:06:48,400
 And this, of course, comes after decades of siege,

132
00:06:48,400 --> 00:06:53,120
 of occupation, of systemic supremacy across the land.

133
00:06:53,120 --> 00:06:56,960
 In the last two years, you've probably only heard

134
00:06:56,960 --> 00:06:58,880
 about Gaza, but in the West Bank,

135
00:06:58,880 --> 00:07:00,880
 on the other side of the land,

136
00:07:00,880 --> 00:07:05,000
 where places like Bethlehem, Ramallah and Jericho are.

137
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:08,680
 So there, Israel also continues to occupy the West Bank,

138
00:07:08,680 --> 00:07:12,720
 building illegal settlements across the land,

139
00:07:12,720 --> 00:07:16,200
 basically fracturing communities, dividing communities.

140
00:07:16,200 --> 00:07:18,960
 I don't know if we, yeah.

141
00:07:18,960 --> 00:07:22,600
 So you can see in the map just the number

142
00:07:22,600 --> 00:07:25,520
 of settlements that are built and you can see how that,

143
00:07:25,520 --> 00:07:28,400
 there's no way to move from Ramallah to Bethlehem

144
00:07:28,400 --> 00:07:31,720
 without passing many checkpoints.

145
00:07:31,720 --> 00:07:35,800
 And of course, these settlers are not just simply there

146
00:07:35,800 --> 00:07:37,720
 and like being good neighbors,

147
00:07:37,720 --> 00:07:40,640
 just on land that's not theirs.

148
00:07:40,640 --> 00:07:42,960
 They're also violent towards Palestinians.

149
00:07:42,960 --> 00:07:46,720
 So scenes of settlers coming to attack people

150
00:07:46,720 --> 00:07:48,880
 in their homes have just become routine

151
00:07:48,880 --> 00:07:50,200
 in the past few months.

152
00:07:50,200 --> 00:07:53,320
 So there's much to talk about when it comes

153
00:07:53,320 --> 00:07:55,000
 to Israel and Palestine.

154
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:57,120
 We can talk about the histories of the region,

155
00:07:57,120 --> 00:07:59,440
 the different starting points of narratives,

156
00:07:59,440 --> 00:08:01,800
 the intricacies of current events,

157
00:08:01,800 --> 00:08:03,880
 and the future visions that seem possible

158
00:08:03,880 --> 00:08:05,680
 or impossible at the moment.

159
00:08:05,680 --> 00:08:07,640
 And entire books have been written about that.

160
00:08:07,640 --> 00:08:10,480
 I'm not gonna try to do that.

161
00:08:10,480 --> 00:08:12,560
 But in the time I have with you this morning,

162
00:08:12,560 --> 00:08:15,200
 I want to offer a different perspective on that.

163
00:08:15,200 --> 00:08:20,200
 I want to ask how can followers of Christ

164
00:08:20,200 --> 00:08:22,880
 respond to these realities I've just described to you?

165
00:08:22,880 --> 00:08:26,080
 How can we respond to realities of violence

166
00:08:26,080 --> 00:08:28,840
 and oppression as followers of Christ?

167
00:08:28,840 --> 00:08:30,680
 Are there certain themes in scripture

168
00:08:30,680 --> 00:08:33,160
 that we can draw upon that can offer us

169
00:08:33,160 --> 00:08:34,800
 a way into this question?

170
00:08:34,800 --> 00:08:37,880
 This afternoon, I want to suggest this idea

171
00:08:37,880 --> 00:08:41,480
 of bearing witness as a tool for faithfully pursuing

172
00:08:41,480 --> 00:08:45,520
 justice and peace, specifically in the case of my homeland.

173
00:08:45,520 --> 00:08:48,080
 To bear witness is different

174
00:08:48,080 --> 00:08:50,640
 than just watching something happen.

175
00:08:50,640 --> 00:08:53,560
 It's to give an account, a testimony.

176
00:08:53,560 --> 00:08:55,960
 It goes beyond simply seeing something,

177
00:08:55,960 --> 00:09:00,360
 happen, it's acting on the experience of seeing something.

178
00:09:00,360 --> 00:09:04,240
 It's demonstrating a type of embodied solidarity.

179
00:09:04,240 --> 00:09:07,480
 And I think this is what our faith calls us to do.

180
00:09:07,480 --> 00:09:10,440
 And to examine this, I want to look into the story of Rispa.

181
00:09:10,440 --> 00:09:13,000
 I don't know how many of you know who Rispa is.

182
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:15,360
 But she's not a biblical character

183
00:09:15,360 --> 00:09:16,680
 that we talk about often.

184
00:09:16,680 --> 00:09:19,560
 Her story kind of is obscure in the Bible.

185
00:09:19,560 --> 00:09:24,040
 And sometimes it's described as tragic, as harrowing.

186
00:09:24,040 --> 00:09:27,760
 I find it to be a story of bravery, of courage.

187
00:09:27,760 --> 00:09:31,320
 I actually find it to be a deeply Palestinian story,

188
00:09:31,320 --> 00:09:34,000
 one that connects so profoundly with the realities

189
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:35,600
 that we see on the ground today.

190
00:09:35,600 --> 00:09:40,160
 So I'll want to read from 2 Samuel.

191
00:09:40,160 --> 00:09:45,760
 If you open your Bibles, I didn't give the team the text.

192
00:09:45,760 --> 00:09:50,760
 So 2 Samuel chapter 21 from verse one.

193
00:09:53,960 --> 00:09:55,640
 It says, "During the reign of David,

194
00:09:55,640 --> 00:09:58,360
 "there was a famine for three successive years.

195
00:09:58,360 --> 00:10:01,440
 "So David sought the face of the Lord.

196
00:10:01,440 --> 00:10:03,380
 "The Lord said, 'It is on account of Saul

197
00:10:03,380 --> 00:10:05,060
 "'and his blood-stained house.

198
00:10:05,060 --> 00:10:08,560
 "'It's because he put the Gibeonites to death.'

199
00:10:08,560 --> 00:10:11,060
 "The king summoned the Gibeonites and spoke to them.

200
00:10:11,060 --> 00:10:12,920
 "Now the Gibeonites were not a part of Israel,

201
00:10:12,920 --> 00:10:14,580
 "but were survivors of the Amorites.

202
00:10:14,580 --> 00:10:16,480
 "The Israelites had sworn to spare them.

203
00:10:16,480 --> 00:10:18,540
 "But Saul and his zeal for Israel and Judah

204
00:10:18,540 --> 00:10:20,380
 "had tried to annihilate them.

205
00:10:20,380 --> 00:10:23,160
 "David asked the Gibeonites, 'What shall I do for you?

206
00:10:23,160 --> 00:10:24,360
 "'How shall I make atonement

207
00:10:24,360 --> 00:10:27,340
 "'so that you will bless the Lord's inheritance?'

208
00:10:27,340 --> 00:10:28,720
 "The Gibeonites answered him,

209
00:10:28,720 --> 00:10:31,320
 "'We have no right to demand silver or gold

210
00:10:31,320 --> 00:10:32,420
 "'from Saul or his family,

211
00:10:32,420 --> 00:10:35,820
 "'nor do we have the right to put anyone in Israel to death.

212
00:10:35,820 --> 00:10:38,800
 "'What do you want me to do for you?' David asked.

213
00:10:38,800 --> 00:10:41,760
 "They answered the king, 'As for the man who destroyed us

214
00:10:41,760 --> 00:10:45,080
 "'and plotted against us, that we have been decimated

215
00:10:45,080 --> 00:10:47,180
 "'and have no place anywhere in Israel,

216
00:10:47,180 --> 00:10:49,620
 "'let seven of his male descendants be given to us

217
00:10:49,620 --> 00:10:52,480
 "'to be killed and their bodies exposed before the Lord

218
00:10:52,480 --> 00:10:55,820
 "'at Gibeah of Saul, the Lord's chosen one.'

219
00:10:55,820 --> 00:10:59,220
 "So the king said, 'I will give them to you.'

220
00:10:59,220 --> 00:11:01,540
 "The king spared Mephibosheth, son of Jonathan,

221
00:11:01,540 --> 00:11:03,640
 "the son of Saul, because of the oath before the Lord

222
00:11:03,640 --> 00:11:06,240
 "between David and Jonathan, son of Saul.

223
00:11:06,240 --> 00:11:08,740
 "But the king took Armoni and Mephibosheth,

224
00:11:08,740 --> 00:11:11,300
 "the two sons of Aiah's daughter Rispa,

225
00:11:11,300 --> 00:11:12,580
 "whom she had born to Saul,

226
00:11:12,580 --> 00:11:15,540
 "together with the five sons of Saul's daughter Merab,

227
00:11:15,540 --> 00:11:17,960
 "who had born, she had born to Adriel,

228
00:11:17,960 --> 00:11:21,420
 "son of Barzillai, the Mehalothite.

229
00:11:21,420 --> 00:11:23,180
 "He handed them over to the Gibeonites,

230
00:11:23,180 --> 00:11:24,960
 "who killed them and exposed their bodies

231
00:11:24,960 --> 00:11:27,120
 "on a hill before the Lord.

232
00:11:27,120 --> 00:11:29,780
 "All seven of them fell together.

233
00:11:29,780 --> 00:11:31,660
 "They were put to death during the first days

234
00:11:31,660 --> 00:11:35,060
 "of the harvest, just as the barley harvest was beginning."

235
00:11:35,060 --> 00:11:37,060
 This is where I want you to pay attention.

236
00:11:37,060 --> 00:11:39,780
 "Rispa, daughter of Aiah, took sackcloth

237
00:11:39,780 --> 00:11:42,900
 "and spread it out for herself on a rock.

238
00:11:42,900 --> 00:11:44,300
 "From the beginning of the harvest

239
00:11:44,300 --> 00:11:46,900
 "till the rain poured down from the heavens on the bodies,

240
00:11:46,900 --> 00:11:49,900
 "she did not let the birds touch them by day

241
00:11:49,900 --> 00:11:52,400
 "or the wild animals by night.

242
00:11:52,400 --> 00:11:54,780
 "When David was told what Aiah's daughter Rispa,

243
00:11:54,780 --> 00:11:56,200
 "Saul's concubine, had done,

244
00:11:56,200 --> 00:11:58,780
 "he went and took the bones of Saul and his son Jonathan

245
00:11:58,780 --> 00:12:01,420
 "from the citizens of Jebuskelad."

246
00:12:01,420 --> 00:12:04,120
 I'll go down to the end of the passage.

247
00:12:04,120 --> 00:12:07,540
 "They buried the bones of Saul and his son Jonathan

248
00:12:07,540 --> 00:12:10,180
 "in the tomb of Saul's father Kish,

249
00:12:10,180 --> 00:12:11,580
 "at Zila and Benjamin,

250
00:12:11,580 --> 00:12:14,060
 "and did everything the king commanded.

251
00:12:14,060 --> 00:12:16,640
 "After that, God answered the prayer

252
00:12:16,640 --> 00:12:19,540
 "in behalf of the land."

253
00:12:19,540 --> 00:12:20,380
 Let's pray.

254
00:12:20,380 --> 00:12:26,080
 Lord, speak to us.

255
00:12:26,080 --> 00:12:29,500
 Through your word, your word is holy,

256
00:12:29,500 --> 00:12:31,460
 your word is powerful.

257
00:12:31,460 --> 00:12:32,720
 Lord, speak to us.

258
00:12:32,720 --> 00:12:35,900
 In Jesus' name we pray, amen.

259
00:12:35,900 --> 00:12:41,500
 I'll give a bit of context to the passage.

260
00:12:41,500 --> 00:12:43,780
 To understand the story of Rispa,

261
00:12:43,780 --> 00:12:46,660
 we need to go back to the days of Joshua.

262
00:12:46,660 --> 00:12:49,580
 During Joshua's time, a peace treaty was made

263
00:12:49,580 --> 00:12:51,620
 between the Israelites and a people group

264
00:12:51,620 --> 00:12:53,860
 called the Gibeonites,

265
00:12:53,860 --> 00:12:56,060
 vowing not to cause them harm.

266
00:12:56,060 --> 00:12:58,940
 Yet it seemed that King Saul, during his reign,

267
00:12:58,940 --> 00:12:59,900
 killed many Gibeonites.

268
00:12:59,900 --> 00:13:02,860
 We're not told this in the Bible, but we can assume.

269
00:13:02,860 --> 00:13:05,180
 And this violation of the treaty

270
00:13:05,180 --> 00:13:06,900
 brought about a famine to the land,

271
00:13:06,900 --> 00:13:09,300
 three-year famine to the land.

272
00:13:09,300 --> 00:13:12,060
 This was during the reign of King David.

273
00:13:12,060 --> 00:13:14,100
 So King David, he wants to remedy the situation,

274
00:13:14,100 --> 00:13:15,980
 he wants to end the famine.

275
00:13:15,980 --> 00:13:18,140
 He sends after the Gibeonites and asks them,

276
00:13:18,140 --> 00:13:21,340
 what can I do for you, how can I remedy the situation?

277
00:13:21,340 --> 00:13:24,420
 The Gibeonites ask for seven descendants of King Saul

278
00:13:24,420 --> 00:13:26,820
 to kill as retribution.

279
00:13:26,820 --> 00:13:29,380
 King David complies with this request

280
00:13:29,380 --> 00:13:31,780
 and hands over seven young men,

281
00:13:31,780 --> 00:13:35,900
 two of them the sons of Rispa, daughters, sorry,

282
00:13:35,900 --> 00:13:38,220
 yeah, two of them the sons of Rispa,

283
00:13:38,220 --> 00:13:41,460
 and five the sons of Saul's daughter, Merab.

284
00:13:41,460 --> 00:13:44,380
 The text tells us that these seven young men

285
00:13:44,380 --> 00:13:46,380
 are killed publicly.

286
00:13:46,380 --> 00:13:48,700
 Some people might say lynched.

287
00:13:48,700 --> 00:13:51,900
 And their bodies are taken up the hill and exposed,

288
00:13:51,900 --> 00:13:53,580
 left to the elements.

289
00:13:53,580 --> 00:13:55,500
 The bodies are not buried properly,

290
00:13:55,500 --> 00:13:59,180
 in violation of religious and cultural norms of the time.

291
00:13:59,180 --> 00:14:01,500
 And this is where Rispa comes in.

292
00:14:01,500 --> 00:14:04,740
 She stages a protest.

293
00:14:04,740 --> 00:14:07,060
 She does an extraordinary thing.

294
00:14:07,060 --> 00:14:11,420
 She's a concubine, she's a sort of a lower status wife,

295
00:14:11,420 --> 00:14:15,140
 but she takes sackcloth as a sign of mourning,

296
00:14:15,140 --> 00:14:19,780
 spreads it out on a rock, on the hill where the bodies lay,

297
00:14:19,780 --> 00:14:21,380
 and she refuses to move.

298
00:14:21,380 --> 00:14:26,980
 The text is quite poetic in how it describes her actions.

299
00:14:26,980 --> 00:14:31,060
 It says, "From the beginning of the harvest

300
00:14:31,060 --> 00:14:33,260
 "till the rain poured down from the heavens,

301
00:14:33,260 --> 00:14:36,420
 "she did not let the birds touch them by day,

302
00:14:36,420 --> 00:14:39,580
 "or the wild animals by night."

303
00:14:39,580 --> 00:14:43,540
 Theologian Wilda Gaffney describes this as follows.

304
00:14:43,540 --> 00:14:45,900
 She says, "Rispa fights with winged,

305
00:14:45,900 --> 00:14:48,420
 "clawed, and toothed scavengers night and day,

306
00:14:48,420 --> 00:14:51,460
 "sleeping, eating, toileting, protecting,

307
00:14:51,460 --> 00:14:54,300
 "and bearing witness."

308
00:14:54,300 --> 00:14:56,740
 Bearing witness.

309
00:14:56,740 --> 00:14:59,980
 What an extraordinary act of courage.

310
00:14:59,980 --> 00:15:02,540
 She stood guard over those bodies.

311
00:15:02,540 --> 00:15:06,020
 A woman on her own, despite the significant threat

312
00:15:06,020 --> 00:15:08,340
 that puts her in, right?

313
00:15:09,180 --> 00:15:12,740
 We can also imagine how heartbreaking that was for Rispa,

314
00:15:12,740 --> 00:15:16,020
 to be sitting there with the injustice that was done to her

315
00:15:16,020 --> 00:15:19,780
 day and night, not knowing whether her actions

316
00:15:19,780 --> 00:15:21,020
 will bear any fruit.

317
00:15:21,020 --> 00:15:26,380
 And the King David, his heart is convicted with this.

318
00:15:26,380 --> 00:15:29,420
 And when he hears what Rispa has done,

319
00:15:29,420 --> 00:15:33,060
 he makes arrangements for the bones to be buried properly,

320
00:15:33,060 --> 00:15:36,620
 to be collected and buried with proper dignity.

321
00:15:36,620 --> 00:15:40,140
 And the story, I don't know if you paid attention to this,

322
00:15:40,140 --> 00:15:42,460
 the story ends with, "After that,

323
00:15:42,460 --> 00:15:44,660
 "only after the bodies are buried,

324
00:15:44,660 --> 00:15:48,060
 "God answered prayer on behalf of the land."

325
00:15:48,060 --> 00:15:50,620
 So the blessing doesn't come with the killing,

326
00:15:50,620 --> 00:15:51,820
 comes with the healing.

327
00:15:51,820 --> 00:15:55,180
 As I mentioned in the beginning,

328
00:15:55,180 --> 00:15:58,900
 I see the story of Rispa's sons unfolding in Palestine today.

329
00:15:58,900 --> 00:16:04,260
 For over a year now, or for over almost two years now,

330
00:16:04,260 --> 00:16:07,140
 Palestinians in Gaza have told us that to die whole

331
00:16:07,140 --> 00:16:10,020
 is a luxury not afforded to many.

332
00:16:10,020 --> 00:16:15,580
 To be buried and grieved has become a privilege

333
00:16:15,580 --> 00:16:17,060
 most people do not have.

334
00:16:17,060 --> 00:16:20,700
 A young lady by the name of Mariam Khatib,

335
00:16:20,700 --> 00:16:23,340
 she's from Gaza, she says, "No one dies complete.

336
00:16:23,340 --> 00:16:27,540
 "After a missile strike, everyone searches in the debris

337
00:16:27,540 --> 00:16:29,500
 "to put their loved ones back together.

338
00:16:29,500 --> 00:16:32,740
 "To be a good mother in the rest of the world

339
00:16:32,740 --> 00:16:36,060
 "is to feed your children good food and keep them warm.

340
00:16:36,060 --> 00:16:37,460
 "But to be a good mother in Gaza

341
00:16:37,460 --> 00:16:39,260
 "is to bury your children whole."

342
00:16:39,260 --> 00:16:44,060
 Mariam went on to describe how her friend, Bouthaina,

343
00:16:44,060 --> 00:16:46,020
 a young woman, a smart young woman

344
00:16:46,020 --> 00:16:47,980
 with a dream to go to medical school,

345
00:16:47,980 --> 00:16:50,060
 was killed by the army.

346
00:16:50,060 --> 00:16:52,780
 Mariam wrote, "I didn't get to cry for her.

347
00:16:52,780 --> 00:16:55,380
 "I didn't get to walk in her funeral.

348
00:16:55,380 --> 00:16:57,180
 "I didn't get to put her body in a grave

349
00:16:57,180 --> 00:17:00,740
 "and visit it every day and lay a rose."

350
00:17:00,740 --> 00:17:02,420
 So as Palestinians, we're very familiar

351
00:17:02,420 --> 00:17:04,700
 with the heartbreak of Rizpa's story.

352
00:17:04,700 --> 00:17:09,140
 The horrors of Rizpa's story are represented today

353
00:17:09,140 --> 00:17:11,020
 across the land.

354
00:17:11,020 --> 00:17:13,140
 The bodies of the seven young men on the hill

355
00:17:13,140 --> 00:17:16,500
 are reflected in the bodies buried under the rubble in Gaza,

356
00:17:16,500 --> 00:17:21,300
 reflected in the bodies of children killed in the West Bank.

357
00:17:21,300 --> 00:17:24,820
 What Rizpa did is bear witness.

358
00:17:24,820 --> 00:17:26,860
 She bore witness to injustice

359
00:17:26,860 --> 00:17:29,860
 and ultimately brought about healing to the land.

360
00:17:29,860 --> 00:17:33,140
 I want to reflect on this text in three points.

361
00:17:33,140 --> 00:17:36,100
 In each, I'll connect what we see in Rizpa's story

362
00:17:36,100 --> 00:17:37,740
 to the realities in my homeland,

363
00:17:37,740 --> 00:17:41,380
 and hopefully that will also give you some idea

364
00:17:41,380 --> 00:17:46,380
 on how you can pray for peace in our land and in yours.

365
00:17:46,380 --> 00:17:51,820
 First, Rizpa bore witness against erasure,

366
00:17:51,820 --> 00:17:53,940
 the erasure of her sons as human beings

367
00:17:53,940 --> 00:17:55,340
 made in the image of God.

368
00:17:55,340 --> 00:17:59,180
 The way those bodies were left on the hill

369
00:17:59,180 --> 00:18:02,300
 was meant to strip the young men of their humanity.

370
00:18:02,300 --> 00:18:06,180
 In Arabic, we say, "Ikram al-mayyad dafno,"

371
00:18:06,180 --> 00:18:09,260
 meaning to give the dead dignity is to bury them.

372
00:18:09,260 --> 00:18:12,060
 The refusal to bury the young men

373
00:18:12,060 --> 00:18:14,420
 was the ultimate sign of humiliation,

374
00:18:14,420 --> 00:18:16,420
 that they are not even considered worthy

375
00:18:16,420 --> 00:18:18,500
 of a proper burial.

376
00:18:18,500 --> 00:18:20,740
 Their lives were considered expendable,

377
00:18:20,740 --> 00:18:22,500
 pawns in a political game.

378
00:18:22,500 --> 00:18:27,900
 Through her vigil, Rizpa fought against that erasure.

379
00:18:27,900 --> 00:18:30,820
 She fought against the attempt to erase her children,

380
00:18:30,820 --> 00:18:33,060
 to dismiss what was done to them.

381
00:18:33,060 --> 00:18:35,940
 She insisted on being recognized.

382
00:18:35,940 --> 00:18:37,700
 She insisted that these young men's lives

383
00:18:37,700 --> 00:18:39,780
 were worthy of grief,

384
00:18:39,780 --> 00:18:41,980
 that they needed to be treated with dignity,

385
00:18:41,980 --> 00:18:44,100
 even in their deaths.

386
00:18:44,100 --> 00:18:47,100
 Throughout the last decades,

387
00:18:47,100 --> 00:18:50,180
 as Palestinians, we've been erased from public discourse.

388
00:18:50,180 --> 00:18:52,340
 Our lives considered expendable.

389
00:18:52,340 --> 00:18:56,060
 Daily reports of Palestinians killed,

390
00:18:56,060 --> 00:18:58,020
 they remain under the radar,

391
00:18:58,020 --> 00:19:00,820
 or when it's reported, it's just numbers, right?

392
00:19:00,820 --> 00:19:03,900
 Statistics, nameless and faceless.

393
00:19:03,900 --> 00:19:06,700
 The numbers, even the numbers of our dead

394
00:19:06,700 --> 00:19:09,660
 are regularly doubted, the perpetrator rarely named.

395
00:19:09,660 --> 00:19:11,220
 So you'll hear in the media,

396
00:19:11,220 --> 00:19:15,540
 Palestinians die as a result of lack of food, starved.

397
00:19:15,540 --> 00:19:22,660
 Palestinians are evacuated, not forcibly displaced.

398
00:19:23,540 --> 00:19:27,300
 Bombs fall, not are dropped intentionally.

399
00:19:27,300 --> 00:19:32,420
 This use of this passive language again and again

400
00:19:32,420 --> 00:19:34,220
 serves to dehumanize us,

401
00:19:34,220 --> 00:19:40,700
 so that our suffering can be justified and explained away.

402
00:19:40,700 --> 00:19:44,380
 Nowadays, our future is discussed and debated

403
00:19:44,380 --> 00:19:47,500
 without a second thought to what we actually want.

404
00:19:47,500 --> 00:19:49,260
 That's erasure.

405
00:19:49,260 --> 00:19:51,820
 Gaza is being reimagined as a business opportunity

406
00:19:51,820 --> 00:19:52,860
 for Donald Trump.

407
00:19:53,860 --> 00:19:57,460
 Palestinians are merely pawns to be moved

408
00:19:57,460 --> 00:20:01,180
 to wherever foreign politicians wish them to be moved.

409
00:20:01,180 --> 00:20:02,140
 This is erasure.

410
00:20:02,140 --> 00:20:06,940
 It pains me to say, but in some Christian circles,

411
00:20:06,940 --> 00:20:08,460
 Palestinians are erased.

412
00:20:08,460 --> 00:20:12,900
 Many Christians believe that the modern state day of Israel

413
00:20:12,900 --> 00:20:14,220
 is the same Israel in the Bible,

414
00:20:14,220 --> 00:20:16,980
 and so to stand with Israel is to stand with God.

415
00:20:16,980 --> 00:20:20,900
 In this theology, Palestinians are either completely erased

416
00:20:20,900 --> 00:20:25,900
 from the narrative, or as are vilified as obstacles

417
00:20:25,900 --> 00:20:27,580
 to the fulfillment of prophecy.

418
00:20:27,580 --> 00:20:32,300
 Rather than being treated as fellow image bearers,

419
00:20:32,300 --> 00:20:33,900
 we are cast aside.

420
00:20:33,900 --> 00:20:38,860
 Theologies that directly impact our lives

421
00:20:38,860 --> 00:20:41,020
 are discussed without us being present.

422
00:20:41,020 --> 00:20:45,020
 There was a video that popped up on my feed the other day.

423
00:20:45,020 --> 00:20:47,260
 It was a pastor who was explaining

424
00:20:48,660 --> 00:20:52,140
 why we need to support the war,

425
00:20:52,140 --> 00:20:54,660
 and it was a seven minute video.

426
00:20:54,660 --> 00:20:57,380
 He had seven minutes, and he could have gone on for more.

427
00:20:57,380 --> 00:20:59,380
 Palestinians were not even mentioned,

428
00:20:59,380 --> 00:21:02,620
 let alone talk of peace, of reconciliation,

429
00:21:02,620 --> 00:21:04,860
 of justice, of dignity, of mercy.

430
00:21:04,860 --> 00:21:08,140
 Many Christians do not even know

431
00:21:08,140 --> 00:21:10,380
 that Palestinian Christians like me exist.

432
00:21:10,380 --> 00:21:12,860
 Many come to visit the land

433
00:21:12,860 --> 00:21:15,300
 and end up visiting the dead stones,

434
00:21:15,300 --> 00:21:17,100
 ignoring the living stones.

435
00:21:18,300 --> 00:21:19,980
 Yes, we do exist.

436
00:21:19,980 --> 00:21:22,180
 We have existed for centuries,

437
00:21:22,180 --> 00:21:24,500
 and we're committed to carrying the message of Christ

438
00:21:24,500 --> 00:21:25,940
 and advancing God's kingdom

439
00:21:25,940 --> 00:21:27,700
 to all those who live in the land.

440
00:21:27,700 --> 00:21:30,380
 We're committed to loving our neighbors,

441
00:21:30,380 --> 00:21:33,540
 whether they're Muslim, Jewish, Druze, or atheists.

442
00:21:33,540 --> 00:21:38,260
 An erasure is not just an oversight.

443
00:21:38,260 --> 00:21:40,940
 It has real life consequences, right?

444
00:21:40,940 --> 00:21:42,460
 When a people group is ignored,

445
00:21:42,460 --> 00:21:44,420
 it's easier to justify complicity

446
00:21:44,420 --> 00:21:46,580
 in their oppression and suffering.

447
00:21:46,580 --> 00:21:51,580
 This leads to a situation where Christians, churches,

448
00:21:51,580 --> 00:21:55,940
 are some of the most ardent supporters

449
00:21:55,940 --> 00:21:57,580
 for land theft in the West Bank.

450
00:21:57,580 --> 00:22:00,140
 I just showed you the settlement, the settlements.

451
00:22:00,140 --> 00:22:02,660
 These settlements require money to build them,

452
00:22:02,660 --> 00:22:04,220
 and a lot of that money, unfortunately,

453
00:22:04,220 --> 00:22:06,660
 is coming from churches.

454
00:22:06,660 --> 00:22:12,620
 I want to tell you about two families in the West Bank.

455
00:22:14,820 --> 00:22:17,380
 Al-Qasiyah family in Makhrur Valley.

456
00:22:17,380 --> 00:22:19,140
 This is on the outskirts of Bethlehem.

457
00:22:19,140 --> 00:22:23,500
 They're a Christian family who have been kicked out

458
00:22:23,500 --> 00:22:25,180
 by settlers from their homes.

459
00:22:25,180 --> 00:22:26,180
 And this is Alice.

460
00:22:26,180 --> 00:22:28,540
 She's one of the daughters of that family,

461
00:22:28,540 --> 00:22:30,060
 and she does a lot of advocacy work

462
00:22:30,060 --> 00:22:33,220
 trying to raise awareness about what's happening

463
00:22:33,220 --> 00:22:35,380
 in her home.

464
00:22:35,380 --> 00:22:37,060
 The other family is the Nassar family.

465
00:22:37,060 --> 00:22:40,140
 If you ever get to come to Bethlehem, to Palestine,

466
00:22:40,140 --> 00:22:41,740
 you can go and visit their farm.

467
00:22:41,740 --> 00:22:45,100
 They have a land that is consistently

468
00:22:45,100 --> 00:22:46,980
 under the threat of displacement.

469
00:22:46,980 --> 00:22:50,780
 They face threats almost daily.

470
00:22:50,780 --> 00:22:53,900
 People coming to attack them, try to steal their land.

471
00:22:53,900 --> 00:22:57,660
 But they have a farm that's just outside of Bethlehem,

472
00:22:57,660 --> 00:22:59,940
 and they are committed to loving their neighbors.

473
00:22:59,940 --> 00:23:04,420
 You walk in and you can see the verse from the Bible

474
00:23:04,420 --> 00:23:06,620
 saying, "Love your enemy."

475
00:23:06,620 --> 00:23:08,380
 We refuse to be enemies.

476
00:23:09,620 --> 00:23:12,420
 They insist on their farm being a place of peacemaking,

477
00:23:12,420 --> 00:23:14,220
 of bridge building, of healing.

478
00:23:14,220 --> 00:23:18,220
 What does it mean then to bear witness against erasure?

479
00:23:18,220 --> 00:23:21,980
 As Rispa did, we bear witness by opening our eyes

480
00:23:21,980 --> 00:23:23,940
 to the suffering of our neighbors,

481
00:23:23,940 --> 00:23:25,740
 despite the pain it may cause.

482
00:23:25,740 --> 00:23:29,260
 We refuse to see them as less than human beings

483
00:23:29,260 --> 00:23:32,580
 made in the image of God, beloved children of God.

484
00:23:32,580 --> 00:23:37,180
 To be a peacemaker does not mean we gloss over the facts,

485
00:23:37,180 --> 00:23:38,980
 or we live in a la-la land.

486
00:23:39,820 --> 00:23:43,420
 No, as peacemakers we must be able to tell the truth.

487
00:23:43,420 --> 00:23:46,940
 To not be afraid to confront harsh realities,

488
00:23:46,940 --> 00:23:48,300
 wherever they may be.

489
00:23:48,300 --> 00:23:51,500
 In Hong Kong, in Palestine, wherever else.

490
00:23:51,500 --> 00:23:58,140
 Second, Rispa bore witness against the apathy of her people.

491
00:23:58,140 --> 00:24:03,620
 So if we look in the text, scholars note that Rispa

492
00:24:03,620 --> 00:24:06,340
 held her vigil for about three to five months, right?

493
00:24:06,340 --> 00:24:08,540
 From the beginning of the harvest to the end.

494
00:24:08,540 --> 00:24:11,860
 We can assume that she encountered a lot of apathy.

495
00:24:11,860 --> 00:24:13,940
 Otherwise, she wouldn't have needed to stay there

496
00:24:13,940 --> 00:24:15,620
 for so long, right?

497
00:24:15,620 --> 00:24:21,660
 I can imagine her on that hill,

498
00:24:21,660 --> 00:24:26,460
 people passing by her, working, eating, drinking,

499
00:24:26,460 --> 00:24:29,020
 just going about their daily lives,

500
00:24:29,020 --> 00:24:32,740
 all while Rispa stood guard over those bodies.

501
00:24:32,740 --> 00:24:35,020
 Yet she refused to concede to that apathy.

502
00:24:36,020 --> 00:24:38,660
 She wailed over the hill, reminding people

503
00:24:38,660 --> 00:24:41,140
 of the injustice that has been done.

504
00:24:41,140 --> 00:24:42,180
 The text is clear.

505
00:24:42,180 --> 00:24:45,420
 Day and night, she stood steadfast, resilient.

506
00:24:45,420 --> 00:24:48,940
 Similarly, we often feel that many people

507
00:24:48,940 --> 00:24:50,820
 are apathetic to our plight.

508
00:24:50,820 --> 00:24:53,420
 That people don't care what happens to us,

509
00:24:53,420 --> 00:24:56,660
 or are caught in the news cycle

510
00:24:56,660 --> 00:24:59,140
 that quickly moves on to the next big thing.

511
00:24:59,140 --> 00:25:02,500
 I've encountered people who assume that our region

512
00:25:02,500 --> 00:25:05,660
 is just bound to be at war.

513
00:25:05,660 --> 00:25:06,900
 I've heard statements like,

514
00:25:06,900 --> 00:25:08,660
 "It's just what happens over there.

515
00:25:08,660 --> 00:25:11,580
 "It's a troublesome neighborhood.

516
00:25:11,580 --> 00:25:16,340
 "There's always violence going on in the Middle East."

517
00:25:16,340 --> 00:25:18,860
 Can you hear how dehumanizing that is?

518
00:25:18,860 --> 00:25:23,420
 Other people cover their apathy with spiritual language.

519
00:25:23,420 --> 00:25:25,380
 So, some people say, "There won't be true peace

520
00:25:25,380 --> 00:25:26,940
 "until Jesus comes anyway."

521
00:25:29,420 --> 00:25:32,220
 And so, they let themselves off the hook

522
00:25:32,220 --> 00:25:35,660
 of their duty as Christians to be peacemakers.

523
00:25:35,660 --> 00:25:40,020
 We can't let ourselves off the hook.

524
00:25:40,020 --> 00:25:41,900
 Palestinian theologian Rula Khoury Mansour,

525
00:25:41,900 --> 00:25:44,860
 she reminds us of our role as followers of Christ.

526
00:25:44,860 --> 00:25:47,020
 She says, "The fact that God has ultimate control

527
00:25:47,020 --> 00:25:49,500
 "of all injustice doesn't release us

528
00:25:49,500 --> 00:25:53,060
 "from our responsibility and mission.

529
00:25:53,060 --> 00:25:55,140
 "Our mission, similar to Jesus',

530
00:25:55,140 --> 00:25:57,500
 "involves being sent to the world to love,

531
00:25:57,620 --> 00:26:00,940
 "serve, teach, heal, save, and free."

532
00:26:00,940 --> 00:26:06,180
 And as Christians, we are especially entangled,

533
00:26:06,180 --> 00:26:07,300
 and I'll tell you why.

534
00:26:07,300 --> 00:26:11,780
 In these past two years,

535
00:26:11,780 --> 00:26:15,420
 we have heard Christian language be used

536
00:26:15,420 --> 00:26:19,980
 to justify war, to justify violence.

537
00:26:19,980 --> 00:26:22,420
 The AI system that Israel uses

538
00:26:22,420 --> 00:26:27,100
 to detect where to drop the bombs,

539
00:26:27,100 --> 00:26:29,300
 do you know what it's called?

540
00:26:29,300 --> 00:26:30,580
 It's called the gospel.

541
00:26:30,580 --> 00:26:35,940
 The good news of Jesus twisted.

542
00:26:35,940 --> 00:26:45,060
 The name of the campaign that is going on right now

543
00:26:45,060 --> 00:26:50,820
 to invade Gaza City, where the Palestinian Christians

544
00:26:50,820 --> 00:26:53,940
 of Gaza are sheltering in the two churches,

545
00:26:53,940 --> 00:26:55,980
 in the Orthodox Church and the Catholic Church.

546
00:26:55,980 --> 00:26:58,180
 All of the Christians are sheltered there.

547
00:26:58,180 --> 00:26:59,740
 There's an operation right now

548
00:26:59,740 --> 00:27:04,140
 that the Israeli army is doing

549
00:27:04,140 --> 00:27:08,940
 to invade that area and to attack in that area.

550
00:27:08,940 --> 00:27:11,700
 Do you know what that campaign is called?

551
00:27:11,700 --> 00:27:13,420
 Gideon's Chariots.

552
00:27:13,420 --> 00:27:19,460
 The use of our Bible, our beloved Bible, friends,

553
00:27:19,460 --> 00:27:22,180
 to justify violence, to give theological cover.

554
00:27:22,180 --> 00:27:25,460
 As Christians, we're entangled in this.

555
00:27:26,460 --> 00:27:28,700
 Martin Luther King, when he wrote the letter

556
00:27:28,700 --> 00:27:31,100
 from Birmingham jail, he was responding to questions

557
00:27:31,100 --> 00:27:32,380
 why he was in Birmingham.

558
00:27:32,380 --> 00:27:34,180
 Birmingham is not his city, right?

559
00:27:34,180 --> 00:27:37,060
 But he was there protesting racial injustice

560
00:27:37,060 --> 00:27:39,780
 and segregation.

561
00:27:39,780 --> 00:27:42,060
 He simply replied, "I'm in Birmingham

562
00:27:42,060 --> 00:27:43,940
 "because injustice is here."

563
00:27:43,940 --> 00:27:46,940
 And he continued, "Injustice anywhere

564
00:27:46,940 --> 00:27:49,740
 "is a threat to justice everywhere."

565
00:27:49,740 --> 00:27:51,940
 We are caught in this, and I love this phrase,

566
00:27:51,940 --> 00:27:55,580
 in an inescapable network of mutuality

567
00:27:55,580 --> 00:27:58,220
 tied in a single garment of destiny.

568
00:27:58,220 --> 00:28:01,900
 Whatever affects one directly affects all indirectly.

569
00:28:01,900 --> 00:28:03,700
 And what Jesus said about the body,

570
00:28:03,700 --> 00:28:07,620
 when one part is hurting, the whole body is hurting.

571
00:28:07,620 --> 00:28:13,980
 And we feel your hurt, and we know that you feel our hurt.

572
00:28:13,980 --> 00:28:18,060
 None of us gets to be apathetic,

573
00:28:18,060 --> 00:28:19,900
 especially as the body of Christ.

574
00:28:21,340 --> 00:28:24,340
 To return to our text, Rispa stood on the hill.

575
00:28:24,340 --> 00:28:26,660
 She did not relent in the face of apathy.

576
00:28:26,660 --> 00:28:31,700
 And scholars point out that the name Rispa means hot coal.

577
00:28:31,700 --> 00:28:37,020
 You know what hot coal represents in the Bible?

578
00:28:37,020 --> 00:28:38,100
 Holiness.

579
00:28:38,100 --> 00:28:41,900
 A call to repentance, right?

580
00:28:41,900 --> 00:28:44,140
 So by her public action, Rispa was acting

581
00:28:44,140 --> 00:28:45,580
 as her name implies.

582
00:28:45,580 --> 00:28:49,620
 She was a hot coal reviving the conscience

583
00:28:49,620 --> 00:28:52,220
 of her community, calling them to acknowledge

584
00:28:52,220 --> 00:28:55,420
 the complicity and the injustice done to these young men.

585
00:28:55,420 --> 00:29:01,300
 Here I want to note two peculiar things.

586
00:29:01,300 --> 00:29:05,660
 First, Rispa stood vigil not only over her two sons,

587
00:29:05,660 --> 00:29:07,980
 but over all seven of them, right?

588
00:29:07,980 --> 00:29:10,940
 There were seven there, only two were hers.

589
00:29:10,940 --> 00:29:13,980
 She led by example, not only caring for her own kin,

590
00:29:13,980 --> 00:29:16,260
 but all those impacted by the injustice.

591
00:29:16,260 --> 00:29:21,260
 And I wonder, did Merab not, why wasn't Merab there?

592
00:29:21,260 --> 00:29:23,140
 Five of her sons were killed.

593
00:29:23,140 --> 00:29:26,740
 We don't know, but I love that image.

594
00:29:26,740 --> 00:29:28,740
 That Rispa was standing there for the people

595
00:29:28,740 --> 00:29:30,060
 who couldn't stand there.

596
00:29:30,060 --> 00:29:32,860
 For everyone.

597
00:29:32,860 --> 00:29:35,660
 I love how South African theologian Alan Bosak

598
00:29:35,660 --> 00:29:37,220
 describes the scene.

599
00:29:37,220 --> 00:29:39,340
 He says, "Rispa says only two children

600
00:29:39,340 --> 00:29:41,180
 "on those crosses are mine.

601
00:29:41,180 --> 00:29:44,220
 "I don't care.

602
00:29:44,260 --> 00:29:47,020
 "Every child on the cross is my child.

603
00:29:47,020 --> 00:29:48,660
 "As long as there is one single child

604
00:29:48,660 --> 00:29:51,020
 "on the cross of pain, of indignity,

605
00:29:51,020 --> 00:29:52,580
 "of suffering and futurelessness,

606
00:29:52,580 --> 00:29:55,700
 "I will stand up and I will fight for that child.

607
00:29:55,700 --> 00:29:57,820
 "Don't ask me whether he is my child.

608
00:29:57,820 --> 00:30:00,420
 "He may not carry my name, but he is my child.

609
00:30:00,420 --> 00:30:01,820
 "She is my child.

610
00:30:01,820 --> 00:30:03,780
 "This is what solidarity means.

611
00:30:03,780 --> 00:30:07,100
 "Every child on a cross is my child."

612
00:30:07,100 --> 00:30:08,540
 This is the spirit of Rispa.

613
00:30:08,540 --> 00:30:12,460
 For us as Palestinian Christians,

614
00:30:12,460 --> 00:30:15,380
 this means we do not get to care only for our kin.

615
00:30:15,380 --> 00:30:19,660
 We don't get to care only for the Palestinian Christians

616
00:30:19,660 --> 00:30:22,100
 or only for the Palestinian victims

617
00:30:22,100 --> 00:30:24,060
 of violence and oppression.

618
00:30:24,060 --> 00:30:26,540
 We insist that every human being

619
00:30:26,540 --> 00:30:27,900
 impacted by this violence,

620
00:30:27,900 --> 00:30:30,060
 Israeli or Palestinian or otherwise,

621
00:30:30,060 --> 00:30:31,340
 is made in the image of God,

622
00:30:31,340 --> 00:30:35,980
 a beloved human being made in the image of God,

623
00:30:35,980 --> 00:30:38,340
 worthy of dignity and honor.

624
00:30:38,340 --> 00:30:40,340
 Every child is our child.

625
00:30:40,340 --> 00:30:42,020
 Everyone who lives between the Jordan River

626
00:30:42,020 --> 00:30:45,020
 and the Mediterranean Sea deserves to live a life

627
00:30:45,020 --> 00:30:46,740
 that is full of safety,

628
00:30:46,740 --> 00:30:50,260
 to have the opportunity to prosper and flourish.

629
00:30:50,260 --> 00:30:52,260
 This is our mission as children of God.

630
00:30:52,260 --> 00:30:57,220
 The second peculiar thing is that those men are already dead.

631
00:30:57,220 --> 00:31:02,380
 Nothing she was gonna do was gonna bring them back to life.

632
00:31:02,380 --> 00:31:04,340
 But Rispa knew that this wasn't about

633
00:31:04,340 --> 00:31:05,780
 bringing the dead to life.

634
00:31:05,780 --> 00:31:09,860
 It was about the conscience of her community.

635
00:31:09,860 --> 00:31:13,060
 What does it mean that this grave injustice happened

636
00:31:13,060 --> 00:31:15,420
 and the community didn't care?

637
00:31:15,420 --> 00:31:16,660
 This was about the community.

638
00:31:16,660 --> 00:31:18,900
 This was about the living, not the dead.

639
00:31:18,900 --> 00:31:22,060
 Notice that God heeds the prayers for the land

640
00:31:22,060 --> 00:31:24,620
 only after the barriers are carried out

641
00:31:24,620 --> 00:31:26,900
 and the harm is addressed.

642
00:31:26,900 --> 00:31:28,820
 Rispa's actions were not only about

643
00:31:28,820 --> 00:31:30,860
 granting dignity to the dead,

644
00:31:30,860 --> 00:31:33,940
 but about healing the land going forward.

645
00:31:33,940 --> 00:31:36,740
 By addressing the past, when we address the past,

646
00:31:36,740 --> 00:31:38,540
 we can move forward in healing.

647
00:31:39,540 --> 00:31:42,100
 How do we bear witness against apathy?

648
00:31:42,100 --> 00:31:44,700
 We do that by taking action,

649
00:31:44,700 --> 00:31:48,740
 by taking action and remaining steadfast.

650
00:31:48,740 --> 00:31:53,060
 And lastly, Rispa bore witness against hopelessness.

651
00:31:53,060 --> 00:31:56,340
 As a woman, as...

652
00:31:56,340 --> 00:31:59,380
 Sorry.

653
00:31:59,380 --> 00:32:03,780
 As a woman, as a widow, as a concubine,

654
00:32:03,780 --> 00:32:06,300
 as a grieving mother who has lost her male child,

655
00:32:06,300 --> 00:32:07,780
 she had very little power.

656
00:32:07,780 --> 00:32:11,060
 Her ability to change things and to demand justice

657
00:32:11,060 --> 00:32:12,900
 seemed very limited.

658
00:32:12,900 --> 00:32:14,060
 By all social measures,

659
00:32:14,060 --> 00:32:16,540
 she was among the weakest in society.

660
00:32:16,540 --> 00:32:19,980
 Even in the text, her words are not recorded.

661
00:32:19,980 --> 00:32:21,300
 We never hear from Rispa.

662
00:32:21,300 --> 00:32:25,220
 Yet she insisted on her agency.

663
00:32:25,220 --> 00:32:27,860
 She did not give into despair.

664
00:32:27,860 --> 00:32:30,220
 She kept her vigil for months.

665
00:32:30,220 --> 00:32:32,460
 I can imagine her enduring the cold

666
00:32:32,460 --> 00:32:35,300
 and the war and the pain.

667
00:32:35,300 --> 00:32:37,180
 And the warm weather.

668
00:32:37,180 --> 00:32:40,860
 She fought off the vultures and wild animals.

669
00:32:40,860 --> 00:32:42,300
 She was relentless,

670
00:32:42,300 --> 00:32:46,420
 much like the persistent widow in Jesus's parable,

671
00:32:46,420 --> 00:32:48,580
 who kept pleading with the unjust judge

672
00:32:48,580 --> 00:32:50,380
 until he granted her justice.

673
00:32:50,380 --> 00:32:54,660
 Rispa demanded dignity even when it seemed beyond reach.

674
00:32:54,660 --> 00:32:58,220
 She hoped against all hope.

675
00:32:58,220 --> 00:33:00,820
 And due to her witness, the king had to act,

676
00:33:00,820 --> 00:33:03,380
 ultimately bringing about the healing of the land.

677
00:33:04,820 --> 00:33:07,660
 In Palestine, after years of systemic injustice

678
00:33:07,660 --> 00:33:10,620
 and dispossession, we often feel hopeless.

679
00:33:10,620 --> 00:33:14,180
 To be honest with you, through human eyes,

680
00:33:14,180 --> 00:33:15,780
 there's not much reason to hope.

681
00:33:15,780 --> 00:33:18,780
 Seems things are only going to get worse.

682
00:33:18,780 --> 00:33:22,500
 But as Christians, as Palestinian Christians,

683
00:33:22,500 --> 00:33:24,620
 we continue to hold on to hope.

684
00:33:24,620 --> 00:33:28,460
 Not as a naive idea or a delusion,

685
00:33:28,460 --> 00:33:32,300
 but as an expression of faith in the God who heals.

686
00:33:33,940 --> 00:33:35,940
 The God who we love and follow.

687
00:33:35,940 --> 00:33:39,460
 Our hope is rooted in God who is just and merciful

688
00:33:39,460 --> 00:33:41,100
 and who is close to the brokenhearted.

689
00:33:41,100 --> 00:33:42,740
 God with us, Emmanuel.

690
00:33:42,740 --> 00:33:47,020
 God who is the advocate of the poor,

691
00:33:47,020 --> 00:33:50,180
 father of the orphans,

692
00:33:50,180 --> 00:33:53,260
 who is to be found among the sick,

693
00:33:53,260 --> 00:33:55,420
 the hungry, and the oppressed,

694
00:33:55,420 --> 00:33:57,580
 who rose from the grave and defeated death.

695
00:33:57,580 --> 00:33:59,500
 Emmanuel, God with us.

696
00:33:59,500 --> 00:34:02,540
 And we express that hope by joining God

697
00:34:02,540 --> 00:34:06,420
 in building his kingdom, by living the Jesus way.

698
00:34:06,420 --> 00:34:08,380
 We hunger and thirst for righteousness,

699
00:34:08,380 --> 00:34:14,300
 not out of selfishness, but out of love for God's kingdom.

700
00:34:14,300 --> 00:34:17,660
 We strive to make peace, to love our enemy,

701
00:34:17,660 --> 00:34:20,140
 until they are transformed into an equal neighbor.

702
00:34:20,140 --> 00:34:23,420
 This is the vision, equal neighbors.

703
00:34:23,420 --> 00:34:25,220
 Until all those who live in the land

704
00:34:25,220 --> 00:34:27,180
 can live in freedom and peace.

705
00:34:27,180 --> 00:34:30,860
 We ask you to hold on to this hope with us.

706
00:34:30,860 --> 00:34:33,940
 To come alongside us as we seek to pursue justice,

707
00:34:33,940 --> 00:34:36,980
 love mercy, and walk humbly with God.

708
00:34:36,980 --> 00:34:38,340
 The journey is not easy,

709
00:34:38,340 --> 00:34:40,340
 but it is the one that we are called to.

710
00:34:40,340 --> 00:34:43,340
 To be Jesus' hands and feet,

711
00:34:43,340 --> 00:34:46,140
 acknowledging one another's humanity and dignity.

712
00:34:46,140 --> 00:34:48,260
 Refusing to remain apathetic,

713
00:34:48,260 --> 00:34:51,420
 to persist in our mission through God's strength.

714
00:34:51,420 --> 00:34:56,460
 My prayer is for God to nurture the spirit of Rispa in us.

715
00:34:56,460 --> 00:34:59,340
 The spirit of bearing witness against erasure,

716
00:34:59,340 --> 00:35:01,820
 against apathy, against hopelessness.

717
00:35:01,820 --> 00:35:05,940
 To be strong in the face of vultures

718
00:35:05,940 --> 00:35:07,860
 that threaten to break our resolve.

719
00:35:07,860 --> 00:35:12,220
 To seek ways to resist violence in an unviolent way.

720
00:35:12,220 --> 00:35:17,180
 To be a hot coal for our communities,

721
00:35:17,180 --> 00:35:20,300
 stirring people to seek out the kingdom of God,

722
00:35:20,300 --> 00:35:23,940
 softening their hearts to God's whispers.

723
00:35:23,940 --> 00:35:28,980
 May God nurture the spirit of Rispa in us all.

724
00:35:28,980 --> 00:35:29,820
 Amen.

725
00:35:29,820 --> 00:35:38,340
 (audience applauding)

726
00:35:38,340 --> 00:35:46,860
 - Sorry, my mic's not working.

727
00:35:46,860 --> 00:35:48,260
 Can you just stand together?

728
00:35:48,260 --> 00:35:49,260
 I'm gonna invite...

729
00:35:49,260 --> 00:35:57,100
 That was deeply profound on multiple levels.

730
00:35:57,300 --> 00:35:59,380
 And I'm just gonna invite, first of all,

731
00:35:59,380 --> 00:36:02,220
 Lama to pray for us.

732
00:36:02,220 --> 00:36:04,780
 And then after that, I'm gonna invite Pastor Ellison

733
00:36:04,780 --> 00:36:07,060
 to pray for Lama and her people.

734
00:36:07,060 --> 00:36:08,580
 And we'll be doing that all together.

735
00:36:08,580 --> 00:36:11,140
 But first, would you pray for us, Lama?

736
00:36:11,140 --> 00:36:16,100
 - Lord Jesus, how much we love you.

737
00:36:16,100 --> 00:36:22,220
 How much we love that you have a different way for us.

738
00:36:22,220 --> 00:36:24,780
 A way out of violence and out of oppression.

739
00:36:25,180 --> 00:36:28,180
 Lord, we may sit at your feet and learn it.

740
00:36:28,180 --> 00:36:34,420
 Lord, I thank you for this church.

741
00:36:34,420 --> 00:36:37,100
 I thank you for their open hearts,

742
00:36:37,100 --> 00:36:39,100
 for their love for you,

743
00:36:39,100 --> 00:36:41,980
 for their heart for justice, for your justice, Lord,

744
00:36:41,980 --> 00:36:43,100
 for your mercy.

745
00:36:43,100 --> 00:36:46,700
 Lord, bless them.

746
00:36:46,700 --> 00:36:51,660
 Help them, Lord, see where they need to be a Rispa.

747
00:36:53,660 --> 00:36:55,420
 Where they need to bear witness.

748
00:36:55,420 --> 00:37:01,340
 Where maybe there's somebody else's children,

749
00:37:01,340 --> 00:37:04,060
 but their parents can't be there to bear witness.

750
00:37:04,060 --> 00:37:06,140
 Help them, Lord, to stand on the hill.

751
00:37:06,140 --> 00:37:11,620
 Lord, help them to weep.

752
00:37:11,620 --> 00:37:14,740
 Help them to rejoice.

753
00:37:14,740 --> 00:37:17,580
 Help them to be courageous.

754
00:37:17,580 --> 00:37:21,860
 Help them to be open.

755
00:37:22,860 --> 00:37:24,220
 Help them to love you more.

756
00:37:24,220 --> 00:37:28,820
 Not, Lord, don't do this work out of selfishness, Lord,

757
00:37:28,820 --> 00:37:30,100
 but out of love for you.

758
00:37:30,100 --> 00:37:31,580
 Purify our hearts.

759
00:37:31,580 --> 00:37:37,180
 May the meditations of our hearts,

760
00:37:37,180 --> 00:37:42,100
 the words of our mouths be pleasing to you, Lord Jesus.

761
00:37:42,100 --> 00:37:44,140
 Amen.

762
00:37:44,140 --> 00:37:45,620
 - Amen.

763
00:37:45,620 --> 00:37:48,060
 I'm gonna just invite Pastor Alison to come and pray.

764
00:37:48,060 --> 00:37:50,700
 - A church of in solidarity with Lama and her people,

765
00:37:50,700 --> 00:37:53,500
 if you would reach out your hands towards her,

766
00:37:53,500 --> 00:37:56,980
 just as a sign that we stand together as we pray.

767
00:37:56,980 --> 00:38:02,180
 And so, Jesus, we thank you for,

768
00:38:02,180 --> 00:38:09,460
 we thank you for bringing Lama here to Hong Kong

769
00:38:09,460 --> 00:38:10,860
 for a time such as this.

770
00:38:10,860 --> 00:38:17,900
 Father, we thank you that you've kept her and protected her,

771
00:38:19,780 --> 00:38:22,020
 and that her voice throughout this weekend, Lord,

772
00:38:22,020 --> 00:38:25,460
 has been maybe a wake-up call,

773
00:38:25,460 --> 00:38:28,620
 something to shake us out of our own apathy

774
00:38:28,620 --> 00:38:30,420
 towards what's been happening.

775
00:38:30,420 --> 00:38:40,060
 And so, Jesus, as we stand now as your family,

776
00:38:40,060 --> 00:38:44,060
 even though our lands are distant in terms of geography,

777
00:38:45,860 --> 00:38:49,260
 Lord, under your love and your care

778
00:38:49,260 --> 00:38:52,940
 and under your banner of love, Lord, there is no distance.

779
00:38:52,940 --> 00:38:57,660
 And that what's happening in Lama's country,

780
00:38:57,660 --> 00:38:59,620
 in the land of Palestine, Lord,

781
00:38:59,620 --> 00:39:03,660
 breaks our hearts, will break our hearts.

782
00:39:03,660 --> 00:39:09,740
 And so we pray that the stories that we've heard,

783
00:39:09,740 --> 00:39:11,980
 the words that Lama has spoken,

784
00:39:11,980 --> 00:39:13,740
 the lives that have been lost,

785
00:39:15,460 --> 00:39:19,060
 Father, we pray that they will not be erased,

786
00:39:19,060 --> 00:39:23,900
 that you've seen and your heart breaks

787
00:39:23,900 --> 00:39:26,460
 with every single person that has lost something,

788
00:39:26,460 --> 00:39:29,900
 for every single family that's been displaced,

789
00:39:29,900 --> 00:39:34,220
 that this breaks and grieves your heart

790
00:39:34,220 --> 00:39:38,620
 to see your children suffer and die under injustice.

791
00:39:43,740 --> 00:39:47,140
 So they will remember, help us to remember, Lord,

792
00:39:47,140 --> 00:39:51,700
 in our own prayer times, in our own quiet times,

793
00:39:51,700 --> 00:39:53,780
 maybe even just for a minute or two, Lord,

794
00:39:53,780 --> 00:39:56,420
 help us to pray for this nation,

795
00:39:56,420 --> 00:39:59,020
 pray for Lama, pray for her people,

796
00:39:59,020 --> 00:40:00,740
 pray for peace in the land.

797
00:40:00,740 --> 00:40:04,700
 And that would stop us from being apathetic, Lord.

798
00:40:04,700 --> 00:40:07,220
 We pray against apathy in our own lives

799
00:40:07,220 --> 00:40:10,500
 just because things here are calm now

800
00:40:10,500 --> 00:40:12,820
 and we've been through our own seasons

801
00:40:12,820 --> 00:40:14,260
 of turmoil in this city, Lord,

802
00:40:14,260 --> 00:40:17,180
 we've had a little taste of what that's like.

803
00:40:17,180 --> 00:40:21,700
 And so, Lord, our hearts are soft,

804
00:40:21,700 --> 00:40:24,700
 help them to remain soft, help apathy not to set in

805
00:40:24,700 --> 00:40:26,900
 just because we're not sure of the facts

806
00:40:26,900 --> 00:40:31,180
 or we don't see it happening before our very eyes.

807
00:40:31,180 --> 00:40:35,540
 As Lama was saying, Lord, as if one part of the body hurts,

808
00:40:35,540 --> 00:40:37,500
 Lord, the whole body hurts.

809
00:40:37,500 --> 00:40:39,740
 And we are the body of Christ.

810
00:40:42,060 --> 00:40:44,460
 So we refuse to let apathy set in,

811
00:40:44,460 --> 00:40:47,580
 keep our hearts soft, keep our minds sharp, Lord,

812
00:40:47,580 --> 00:40:51,300
 to what's going on, so we refuse to forget.

813
00:40:51,300 --> 00:40:57,220
 And ultimately, Lord, we refuse

814
00:40:57,220 --> 00:40:59,180
 to also give in to hopelessness.

815
00:40:59,180 --> 00:41:05,300
 Lord, like the words of Mary herself,

816
00:41:05,300 --> 00:41:07,500
 with God, all things are possible.

817
00:41:07,500 --> 00:41:09,860
 Like Danielle spoke of, we just need faith

818
00:41:09,860 --> 00:41:13,620
 as small as a mustard seed to see mountains move

819
00:41:13,620 --> 00:41:15,700
 and this is a huge mountain,

820
00:41:15,700 --> 00:41:17,820
 this is gonna require a huge amount of faith

821
00:41:17,820 --> 00:41:21,180
 and a huge amount of hope.

822
00:41:21,180 --> 00:41:23,340
 But Lord, you are the God of all hope.

823
00:41:23,340 --> 00:41:26,100
 You are the definition of hope.

824
00:41:26,100 --> 00:41:29,580
 Even death could not hold you down.

825
00:41:29,580 --> 00:41:32,540
 And so we pray against hopelessness,

826
00:41:32,540 --> 00:41:35,180
 we pray for hope to be restored,

827
00:41:35,180 --> 00:41:36,620
 we pray for peace in the land,

828
00:41:36,620 --> 00:41:40,580
 we pray for the perpetrators of this

829
00:41:40,580 --> 00:41:42,860
 to have a change of their hearts, Lord,

830
00:41:42,860 --> 00:41:44,700
 in the way we pray for our enemies, Lord,

831
00:41:44,700 --> 00:41:46,380
 that you would convict them in a way

832
00:41:46,380 --> 00:41:50,100
 that only you can and only they can understand,

833
00:41:50,100 --> 00:41:51,540
 that they would come to their senses

834
00:41:51,540 --> 00:41:54,540
 and realize that war will never lead us to anywhere.

835
00:41:54,540 --> 00:42:00,180
 But what we need is your love, your mercy,

836
00:42:00,180 --> 00:42:02,500
 your grace, your kingdom, your economy,

837
00:42:02,500 --> 00:42:04,260
 your way of doing things,

838
00:42:04,620 --> 00:42:07,420
 your mind to transform and renew

839
00:42:07,420 --> 00:42:09,420
 each and every single person, Lord.

840
00:42:09,420 --> 00:42:13,180
 And Lord, as the llama travels back, Lord,

841
00:42:13,180 --> 00:42:16,980
 as she continues her work, Lord,

842
00:42:16,980 --> 00:42:19,180
 fill her up with courage, fill her up with strength,

843
00:42:19,180 --> 00:42:22,340
 fill her up, protect her from harm, Lord,

844
00:42:22,340 --> 00:42:24,940
 fill her up with everything that she needs, Lord,

845
00:42:24,940 --> 00:42:28,180
 that her voice, Lord, would not be silenced,

846
00:42:28,180 --> 00:42:29,780
 that her voice would ring loudly

847
00:42:29,780 --> 00:42:31,580
 to those who need to hear it

848
00:42:31,620 --> 00:42:34,540
 and that as she stands firm on her convictions

849
00:42:34,540 --> 00:42:35,900
 and her faith in you,

850
00:42:35,900 --> 00:42:38,780
 we stand together in solidarity with her

851
00:42:38,780 --> 00:42:41,820
 as brothers and sisters in Christ.

852
00:42:41,820 --> 00:42:42,940
 Protect her with your love,

853
00:42:42,940 --> 00:42:44,940
 protect her with your Holy Spirit, Lord.

854
00:42:44,940 --> 00:42:50,180
 And we say, we pray all of this

855
00:42:50,180 --> 00:42:51,860
 in the all-loving, all-powerful,

856
00:42:51,860 --> 00:42:55,700
 the only name that is able to cast out all enemies,

857
00:42:55,700 --> 00:42:58,460
 only name that's able to bring peace into the land,

858
00:42:58,460 --> 00:43:01,740
 it's the name of Jesus, all-powerful name,

859
00:43:01,740 --> 00:43:03,220
 that we pray.

860
00:43:03,220 --> 00:43:05,540
 And the church says, amen.

861
00:43:05,540 --> 00:43:08,700
 (audience applauding)

862
00:43:08,700 --> 00:43:15,500
 >> We're gonna take a time just to worship,

863
00:43:15,500 --> 00:43:18,620
 and I think it's important that we respond that way

864
00:43:18,620 --> 00:43:22,380
 as that prophetic act against hopelessness.

865
00:43:22,380 --> 00:43:23,860
 We've heard some pretty deep

866
00:43:23,860 --> 00:43:25,660
 and challenging things this evening,

867
00:43:25,700 --> 00:43:27,940
 and it's good.

868
00:43:27,940 --> 00:43:28,980
 It's good to be shaken up.

869
00:43:28,980 --> 00:43:30,940
 It's good for us to understand what's happening.

870
00:43:30,940 --> 00:43:33,020
 It's good to hear it firsthand that way

871
00:43:33,020 --> 00:43:36,980
 and to see how so often even our own faith,

872
00:43:36,980 --> 00:43:39,780
 our own language, our own Christian theology

873
00:43:39,780 --> 00:43:42,980
 can work against the very things of the gospel.

874
00:43:42,980 --> 00:43:45,340
 But we stand here at the Vine in solidarity

875
00:43:45,340 --> 00:43:48,420
 to all the things that Lama was sharing,

876
00:43:48,420 --> 00:43:50,260
 and one of the ways in which we do that

877
00:43:50,260 --> 00:43:52,940
 as the body of Christ is in a place of prayer,

878
00:43:52,940 --> 00:43:53,940
 as we've already done,

879
00:43:53,940 --> 00:43:56,580
 and then secondly, in a place of worship,

880
00:43:56,580 --> 00:44:00,180
 to say that the enemy is not gonna have the final say, amen,

881
00:44:00,180 --> 00:44:02,700
 is to say that we are gonna proclaim with our mouths

882
00:44:02,700 --> 00:44:04,580
 and with our tongues that he is king and king,

883
00:44:04,580 --> 00:44:06,860
 Lord of lords, and that he can do the very things

884
00:44:06,860 --> 00:44:08,300
 that we've been hearing and talking about today.

885
00:44:08,300 --> 00:44:11,060
 So we're gonna spend some time in worship,

886
00:44:11,060 --> 00:44:12,100
 and then I'll come in a few minutes

887
00:44:12,100 --> 00:44:12,980
 and just close our time.

888
00:44:12,980 --> 00:44:15,920
 But let's praise our Lord together as a community.

889
00:44:15,920 --> 00:44:16,760
 Amen.

890
00:44:16,760 --> 00:44:26,760
 [BLANK_AUDIO]

